{"id":"astro-ph/9611165","submitter":"Nick Gnedin","authors":"Nickolay Y. Gnedin","title":"Incorporating Radiative Cooling into a Cosmological Hydrodynamic Code","comments":"submitted to MNRAS","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1093/mnras/289.4.927","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  A possible inconsistency arising when a radiative cooling term is\nincorporated in a finite resolution self-gravitating hydrodynamic code is\ndiscussed. The inconsistency appears when the heating-cooling balance within\nthe cooling and collapsing gas cloud is broken near the resolution limit of a\nnumerical code. As the result, the cooling time of a fluid element increases\nenormously leading to the unphysical conclusion that the fluid element does not\ncool and is therefore stable against the collapse. A special cooling\nconsistency condition is introduced which approximately restores the\nheating-cooling balance and leads to a numerical solution that closely mimics\nthe exact (infinite resolution) solution.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 20 Nov 1996 19:27:16 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 24 Feb 1997 22:49:14 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-24"}
